Clustering - Electricity Demand (Unsupervised Learning)¶

Description¶

Studying the electric demand of clients in Portugal during 2013 and 2014.

The data contains 370 time series, corresponding to the electric demand for 370 clients, between 2011 and 2014.

Data:¶

https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/ElectricityLoadDiagrams20112014#

The dataframe contains a row for each interval of 15 minutes between Jan 1, 2011 to Dec 31 2014. There are 370 columns (370 clients). The dataframe is indexed by a timestamp.¶

  • Frequency is 15 minutes, each day provides 24 x 4 = 96 datapoints
  • 96 multiplied by 365 days and 4 years (plus 1 day in Feb 29, 2012) gives: 96 x 365 x 4 + 96 = 140256 (seen in data.shape)

Clustering Analysis¶

I created two models, one for k means and one for the agglomerative clustering model. I plotted inertia1, inertia2 and silhoutte for k means. For the agglomerative clustering model I plotted the silhoutte score. This in essence will find the optimal number of clusters

Below, you can see from the graphs the optimal number of clusters is 6 when performing kmeans. When we look at the inertia, we can see the bend in the knee at this value, as well, when we look at the silhouette graph, we also see the highest point to be at 6.

In terms of the agglomerative clustering model, the optimal number of clusters seems to be at 5, we can see this again at the highest point in the graph

In [27]:
inertias_1 = []
inertias_2 = []
silhouette_avgs = []
max_K = 15
for k in np.arange(1,max_K+1):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=0).fit(X)    
    inertias_1 = inertias_1 + [kmeans.inertia_]
    inertias_2 = inertias_2 + [getInertia2(X,kmeans)]
    if k>1:
        silhouette_avgs = silhouette_avgs + [silhouette_score(X, kmeans.labels_)]

plt.figure(figsize=(20,5))

plt.subplot(1,3,1)
plt.title("Inertia_1: sum square distances to closest cluster")
plt.plot(np.arange(1,max_K+1),inertias_1)
plt.xticks(np.arange(1,max_K+1))
plt.xlabel('number of clusters')
plt.grid()
    
plt.subplot(1,3,2)    
plt.title("Ratio: Inertia_1 VS. sum square distances to 2nd closest cluster")
plt.plot(np.arange(1,max_K+1),np.array(inertias_1)/np.array(inertias_2))
plt.xticks(np.arange(1,max_K+1))
plt.xlabel('number of clusters')
plt.grid()

plt.subplot(1,3,3)  
plt.title("Average Silhouette")
plt.plot(np.arange(2,max_K+1), silhouette_avgs)
plt.xticks(np.arange(2,max_K+1))
plt.xlabel('number of clusters')
plt.grid()

plt.show()
In [28]:
silhouette_avgs = []
max_K = 15
for k in np.arange(1,max_K+1):
    agg_c = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=k).fit(X)    
    if k>1:
        silhouette_avgs = silhouette_avgs + [silhouette_score(X, agg_c.labels_)]

plt.plot(np.arange(2,max_K+1), silhouette_avgs)
plt.title("Average Silhouette: Agglomerative Clustering")
plt.xticks(np.arange(2,max_K+1))
plt.xlabel('number of clusters')
plt.grid()

plt.show()

I plotted 2 graphs for the k means model, the curves for all the clusters because I could segment the curves to each cluster, and the centroid curve as well. However, for the agglomerative clustering model, I was only able to get the curves that belond to each cluster. Since I wasn't able to get the coordinates for the centroids, it was difficult for me to be able to plot this.

Kmeans Model¶

In [29]:
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=6, random_state = 42)
kmeans = kmeans.fit(X)
kmeans_labels = kmeans.labels_   #obtaining labels for clusters
kmeans_centers = kmeans.cluster_centers_   #obtaining centroid curves for data
data_clustered = pd.DataFrame(X.T, columns = kmeans_labels)   #putting it back into a dataframe to plot with the labels
centroid_curves = pd.DataFrame(kmeans_centers.T)   #putting it back into a dataframe to plot the centroids

print("The number of clients in each cluster are...")
print("Cluster 1:", (kmeans_labels == 0).sum())
print("Cluster 2:", (kmeans_labels == 1).sum())
print("Cluster 3:", (kmeans_labels == 2).sum())
print("Cluster 4:", (kmeans_labels == 3).sum())
print("Cluster 5:", (kmeans_labels == 4).sum())
print("Cluster 6:", (kmeans_labels == 5).sum())
